Here are the key steps: 1. **Calculate the energy of the incoming photon**: \[ E_{\text{photon}} = h \nu = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s} \times 3.091 \times 10^{14} \, \text{Hz} \approx 2.048 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] 2. **Subtract the band gap energy from the photon energy** to find the kinetic energy of the photoelectron: \[ E_{\text{kinetic}} = E_{\text{photon}} - E_{\text{gap}} = 2.048 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} - 1.1214 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \approx 0.9266 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] 3. **Convert the kinetic energy to joules** (already done in step 1). 4. **Calculate the de Broglie wavelength** of the photoelectron using the formula \(\lambda = \frac{h}{\sqrt{2 m_e E_{\text{kinetic}}}}\): \[ \sqrt{2 m_e E_{\text{kinetic}}} = \sqrt{2 \times 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \text{kg} \times 9.2916 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{J}} \approx 1.298 \times 10^{-25} \, \text{kg·m/s} \] \[ \lambda = \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}}{1.298 \times 10^{-25} \, \text{kg·m/s}} \approx 5.09 \times 10^{-10} \, \text{m} \] Thus, the wavelength of the photoemission is \(\boxed{5.09 \times 10^{-10}}\) meters.
